{{short description|proposed species of amphibian}} {{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}} {{italictitle}} <!--- COMMENTED OUT PENDING FORMAL PUBLICATION OF NAME {{Speciesbox | image = | image_alt = | image_caption = | status = | status_system = | status_ref = | genus = Dermophis | species = donaldtrumpi | authority = | synonyms = | synonyms_ref = | subdivision_ranks = | subdivision = }}---> '''''Dermophis donaldtrumpi''''' is a proposed [[species]] of [[caecilian]] {{endash}} a nearly-blind, serpentine [[amphibian]] {{endash}} to be named after [[Donald Trump]]. It was originally discovered in [[Panama]] and is yet to be confirmed as a new species; as of {{Currentmonth}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}, the [[binomial name]] has not been formally published. It was given its name after the [[Rainforest Trust]] held an auction for the naming rights. The company [[EnviroBuild]] won the auction and named the species in protest against [[Environmental policy of the Donald Trump administration|Trump's environmental policies]] and views.<ref name="snopes">{{cite web |first=Dan |last=MacGuill |url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/dermophis-donaldtrumpi-amphibian-trump/ |date=December 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |title=Was a Newly-Discovered Species of Amphibian Given the Name 'Dermophis Donaldtrumpi'?|website=[[Snopes]]}}</ref>
==Description== ''Dermophis donaldtrumpi'' is about {{convert|10|cm|in|0}} long, shiny, slippery, and slimy, with the appearance of a large [[worm]]. It is a [[burrowing]] species, living almost entirely [[Subterranea (geography)|underground]].{{r|sfgate}}{{r|guardian}}<ref name="usa" /> It is nearly blind, with its eyes only able to detect light and dark, so it uses a pair of [[tentacle]]s near its mouth in order to find prey; it also has an extra layer of skin which its young can eat after peeling it off.{{r|sfgate}}
According to the [[Rainforest Trust]], amphibians such as ''D. donaldtrumpi'' are vulnerable to extinction due to being exceptionally sensitive to the results of [[global warming]].{{r|guardian}}
==Naming== In December 2018, the [[Rainforest Trust]] completed an auction of naming rights for twelve newly discovered species of South American plants and animals,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/06/science/species-naming-auction-rainforest-trust.html|title=Want to Name a New Frog? A Whiskered Mouse? An Orchid? Be the Highest Bidder|first=Julia|last=Jacobs|date=December 6, 2018|accessdate=December 22, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> the money going towards the conservation of the species' habitats.<ref name=guardian/> The sustainable building materials company EnviroBuild paid $25,000 for the right to name the new amphibian.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rainforesttrust.org/species-legacy-auction-is-a-resounding-win-for-wildlife-conservation/|title=Species Legacy Auction is a Resounding Win for Wildlife Conservation|last=Antram|first=Alex|date=|work=[[Rainforest Trust]]|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>
Aidan Bell, owner of EnviroBuild, stated that he named the species after Trump to raise awareness of Trump's policies on [[climate change]] and the danger that he sees those policies pose to the survival of many species. Referring to the creature's "rudimentary eyes which can only detect light or dark", Bell said that "Capable of seeing the world only in black and white, Donald Trump has claimed that climate change is a hoax by the Chinese."<ref name="snopes"/><ref name="guardian">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/dec/18/blind-amphibian-named-after-trumps-climate-change-stance|title=Blind creature that buries head in sand named after Donald Trump|last=Carrington|first=Damian|date=December 18, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.envirobuild.com/blogs/articles/donald-trump-amphibian|title=EnviroBuild name an amphibian in honour of Donald Trump's commitment to environmental issues.|last=Bell|first=Aidan|date=December 18, 2018|work=EnviroBuild|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/421934-blind-amphibian-that-buries-head-in-sand-named-after-trump|title=Blind amphibian that buries head in sand named after Trump|last=Daughtery|first=Owen|date=December 18, 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' also linked the creature's limited sight as "a feature that inspired it[s] name."<ref name="mirror">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/science/blind-amphibian-loves-burrowing-head-13755117|title=Blind amphibian that loves burrowing head in sand is named after DONALD TRUMP|last=Best|first=Shivali|date=December 19, 2018|website=Daily Mirror|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', "The naming choice highlights the president’s dismal approval ratings worldwide and is clearly designed to belittle him."<ref name="wapo">{{cite news |title=A blind, wormlike amphibian that burrows underground has been named after Donald Trump |newspaper=The Washington Post |first=Isaac |last=Stanley-Becker |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/12/19/blind-worm-like-amphibian-that-buries-its-head-underground-has-been-named-after-donald-trump/ |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |date=December 19, 2018}}</ref>
Bell also related the caecilian's instincts when nurturing young to what he claims as Trump's [[nepotism]]: "The dermophis genus grows an extra layer of skin which their young use their teeth to peel off and eat, a behaviour known as dermatrophy.{{sic}} As a method of ensuring [his] children survive in life Donald Trump prefers granting them high roles in the [[Oval Office]]."<ref name="snopes"/> [[Dermatotrophy]], a form of parental care in which the young feed on the skin of its mother, has been scientifically observed in other species of caecilians, such as ''[[Boulengerula taitana]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkinson|first=Mark|last2=Nussbaum|first2=Ronald A.|last3=Greven|first3=Hartmut|last4=Jared|first4=Carlos|last5=Antoniazzi|first5=Marta M.|last6=Müller|first6=Hendrik|last7=Kupfer|first7=Alexander|date=April 2006|title=Parental investment by skin feeding in a caecilian amphibian|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=440|issue=7086|pages=926–929|doi=10.1038/nature04403|pmid=16612382|issn=1476-4687|bibcode=2006Natur.440..926K|hdl=2027.42/62957|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/62957/1/nature04403.pdf}}</ref>
EnviroBuild further connected the amphibian's nature to [[burrow]] underground with more of the president's policies: “Burrowing its head underground helps Donald Trump when avoiding scientific consensus on anthropogenic climate change".<ref name="mirror" /> The company also noted that he had "appointed several energy lobbyists to the [[EPA|Environment Agency]], where their job is to regulate the energy industry.”<ref name="mirror" />
The process of naming this species has garnered significant controversy among researchers and conservationists; some have pointed out the conservation benefits of the money donated to name the species, while others have criticized the idea of donating to name a new species, as many of the donors had no involvement with the studies undertaken to describe the species. In particular, [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]] researcher Christian Kammerer sees the facetious name of the amphibian as "just mean to the creature". <ref>{{Cite web |date=April 12, 2019 |url=https://qz.com/1593968/the-pros-and-cons-of-letting-the-public-name-a-new-species/|title=Letting the public name a newly discovered species could go horribly wrong|last=Montanari|first=Shaena|last2=Montanari|first2=Shaena|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>{{notelist}}
