'''''Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP''''', No. 19-715, is a pending [[Supreme Court of the United States]] case involving the [[tax returns of Donald Trump|tax returns of President Donald Trump]].<ref name="SCOTUSdocket">[https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/19-715.html]</ref>
==Background== {{see|List of lawsuits involving Donald Trump}}
The House Oversight Committee had subpoenaed numerous records from the President's accounting firm, Mazars, Deutsche Bank and other companies. The President sued, and the subpoena was blocked while the case wound its way through the courts, losing in district court and on appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/18/supreme-court-temporarily-halts-court-order-requiring-accountants-to-turn-over-trumps-tax-returns-to-congress.html|title=Supreme Court temporarily halts court order requiring accountants to turn over Trump's tax returns to Congress|first=Tucker Higgins,Jacob|last=Pramuk|date=November 18, 2019|website=CNBC}}</ref> The Supreme Court agreed to continue the block for a few days, ordering the House Counsel to submit a rebuttal by November 21, which it did.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2019-11-21/house-attorneys-say-trumps-tax-returns-needed-for-impeachment-inquiry|title=House attorneys say Trump's tax returns are needed for impeachment inquiry|date=November 22, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> In seeking a rapid subpoena ruling, House general counsel [[Douglas Letter]] wrote, "The president certainly has no right to dictate the timetable by which third parties provide information that could potentially be relevant to that inquiry."<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.rollcall.com/2019/11/21/democrats-seek-quick-subpoena-ruling-in-trump-tax-records-case/|newspaper=Roll Call|date=November 21, 2019|author=Todd Ruger|title=Democrats seek quick subpoena ruling in Trump tax records case}}</ref>
The target of the subpoena (Mazars) has said that it is willing to comply with the subpoena; Trump's lawsuit against Mazars, brought in his personal capacity, has delayed Mazars' response.<ref name=Lederman>{{cite web|author=Marty Lederman|url=https://www.justsecurity.org/67461/understanding-the-two-mazars-subpoena-cases-before-the-supreme-court/|title=Understanding the Two Mazars Subpoena Cases Before the Supreme Court|date=November 25, 2019|website=Just Security}}</ref> Legal scholar [[Marty Lederman]] has described the ''Mazars'' case as more important than the ''Trump v. Vance'' case.<ref name=Lederman/> Lederman describes Trump's argument&mdash;that Congress entirely lacks "constitutional authority to investigate a sitting President's possible conflicts of interest and violations of law"&mdash;as an "alarming" assertion that, "would, if credited, be a radical departure from our constitutional history and tradition."<ref name=Lederman/>
==D.C. Circuit== ===Ruling=== Circuit Judge [[David S. Tatel]] wrote the majority opinion, which was joined by Circuit Judge [[Patricia Millett]].<ref name="circuitopinions">{{cite court |litigants=Trump v. Comm. on Oversight & Reform |vol=940 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=710 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.C. Cir.]] |date=2019 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20191011141 |accessdate=2019-12-19 |quote=}}</ref>
===Dissent=== Circuit Judge [[Neomi Rao]] dissented, insisting that the impeachment power is the only legitimate method for such congressional investigations.<ref name="circuitopinions"/>
===''En banc'' rehearing denied=== On November 13, 2019, the D.C. Circuit denied the Trump administration's petition for an ''[[en banc]]'' rehearing. [[Gregory Katsas]], [[Neomi Rao]], and [[Karen Henderson]] dissented from the denial of rehearing.<ref name="noenbanc">{{cite court |litigants=Trump v. Comm. on Oversight & Reform |vol= |reporter=No. |opinion=19-5142 |pinpoint= |court=D.C. Cir. |date=Nov. 13, 2019 |url=https://www.cadc.uscourts.gov/internet/opinions.nsf/2D73A7890FAEE374852584B100822F92/$file/19-5142-1815681.pdf |accessdate=2019-12-19 |quote=}}</ref>
==Supreme Court== The question facing the Supreme Court is whether the U.S. House of Representatives has the authority to issue subpoenas to obtain the private financial records of the president and his businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/trump-v-mazars/|website=SCOTUSblog|language=en|access-date=2020-05-21}}</ref>
On November 25, 2019, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] granted a stay of the D.C. Circuit's ruling extending the time for the appealing party (Trump) to file a petition for a writ of ''[[certiorari]]'', asking the Court to hear the case.<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/112519zr_7l48.pdf 19A545 TRUMP, DONALD J., ET AL. V. MAZARS USA, LLP, ET AL.] supremecourt.gov November 25, 2019</ref> Trump's legal team filed the petition on December 5, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/05/politics/trump-appeal-supreme-court-house-subpoena-mazars/index.html |title=Trump asks Supreme Court to block House subpoena for financial documents and take up case |author=Ariane de Vogue |date=December 5, 2019 |website=cnn.com |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> and on December 13, 2019, the Supreme Court granted certiorari and consolidated the case with ''[[Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG]]''.<ref name="SCOTUSdocket" />
Oral arguments was originally scheduled to take place on March 31, 2020, but two weeks before the arguments were to take place, the Supreme Court postponed arguments in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] and waited one month to announce the rescheduled date. In April 2020, the Supreme Court said that oral argument in the ''Mazars'' case and other cases would be heard by telephone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/13/833292153/supreme-court-to-hear-arguments-by-telephone-including-on-trumps-financial-recor|title=Supreme Court To Hear Arguments By Telephone, Including On Trump's Financial Records|last=Totenberg|first=Nina|date=13 April 2020|website=NPR.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/publicinfo/press/pressreleases/pr_04-13-20|title=Press Releases - April 13, 2020 - Supreme Court of the United States|last=|first=|date=|website=[[SupremeCourt.gov]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Consolidated oral arguments for ''Trump v. Mazars'' and ''Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG'', as well as ''Trump v. Vance'', were heard on May 12.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The stakes of Trump's tax return case couldn't be higher|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/05/11/opinions/trump-tax-returns-supreme-court-stakes-honig/index.html|last=Honig|first=Elie|date=11 May 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref> In arguing against the need for subpoenas for tax returns, Deputy Solicitor General Jeffrey Wall repeatedly cited that they presented "dangers of harassing and distracting and undermining the President".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lederman |first1=Marty |title=Trump’s DOJ Says the President Would Be “Undermined” if His Tax Records Were Revealed |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/05/trumps-doj-mazars-tax-returns-revealed.html |accessdate=May 16, 2020 |work=[[Slate (website)|Slate]] |date=May 15, 2020}}</ref>
Congressional subpoenas related to this case will expire with the end of the 116th Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Coronavirus May Keep Trump’s Financial Records Under Wraps Forever|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/trump-supreme-court-mazars-deutsche-bank-vance-delay.html|last=Stahl|first=Jeremy|date=2020-03-16|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>
