{{update|delay in (Argument) dates due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United States]]|date=March 2020}} <!--{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG |Docket=19-760 |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate= |DecideYear= |FullName=Donald J. Trump, et al. v Deutsche Bank AG, et al. |Prior= Preliminary injunction denied, ''Donald J. Trump, et al. v Deutsche Bank AG, et al.'', No. [https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.nysd.514634/gov.uscourts.nysd.514634.59.0.pdf 1:19-cv-03826-ER] ([[S.D.N.Y.]] 2019); affirmed, 940 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20191010073 146] ([[2d Cir.]] 2019); stay granted, Application No. 19A640 (S. Ct. 2019); cert. granted, consolidated with D.C. Circuit's ''Donald J. Trump, et al. v. Mazars USA, LLP and Committee on Oversight and Reform of the U.S. House of Representatives'', No. 19-715 (S. Ct. 2019) |Subsequent= |Holding= |PerCuriam= |Majority= |JoinMajority= |Concurrence= |JoinConcurrence= |Concurrence/Dissent= |JoinConcurrence/Dissent= |Dissent= |JoinDissent= |LawsApplied= }}--> {{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Trump v. Deutsche Bank, AG |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=August 23, |ArgueYear=2019 |DecideDate=December 6, |DecideYear=2019 |FullName=Donald J. Trump, et al. v Deutsche Bank AG, et al. |Citations=940 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20191010073 146], No. [http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/29700093-a5d7-45ea-9738-04a53a4ca36a/8/doc/19-1540_complete_opn.pdf#xml=http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/29700093-a5d7-45ea-9738-04a53a4ca36a/8/hilite/ 19-1540-cv] |Prior= Preliminary injunction denied, ''Donald J. Trump, et al. v Deutsche Bank AG, et al.'', No. [https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.nysd.514634/gov.uscourts.nysd.514634.59.0.pdf 1:19-cv-03826-ER] (S.D.N.Y. 2019) |Subsequent=Stay granted, Application No. 19A640 (S. Ct. 2019); cert. granted, No. [https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121319zr_1a7d.pdf 19-760], consolidated with D.C. Circuit's ''Donald J. Trump, et al. v. Mazars USA, LLP and Committee on Oversight and Reform of the U.S. House of Representatives'', No. 19-715 (S. Ct. 2019) |Holding= |Judges=''Circuit Judges'' [[Peter W. Hall]], [[Debra Ann Livingston]], ''Senior Circuit Judge'' [[Jon O. Newman]] |PerCuriam= |Majority=Newman |JoinMajority=Hall |Concurrence= |JoinConcurrence= |Concurrence/Dissent=Livingston |JoinConcurrence/Dissent= |Dissent= |JoinDissent= |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG''''', No. 19-760, is a pending [[Supreme Court of the United States]] case involving the [[tax returns of Donald Trump|tax returns of President Donald Trump]].
==Background== {{see|List of lawsuits involving Donald Trump}}
==Second Circuit== {{expand section|date=May 2020}} ===Ruling===
===Concurrence/dissent===
==Supreme Court== The question facing the Supreme Court is whether the U.S. House of Representatives has the authority to issue subpoenas to obtain the private financial records of the president and his businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/trump-v-deutsche-bank-ag/|website=SCOTUSblog|language=en|access-date=2020-05-21}}</ref>
On December 13, 2019, the Supreme Court consolidated the case with ''[[Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP|Trump v. Mazars]]''.<ref name="SCOTUSdocket">[https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/19-715.html]</ref>
Oral arguments were originally scheduled to take place on March 31, 2020, but two weeks before the arguments were to take place, the Supreme Court postponed arguments in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] and waited one month to announce the rescheduled date. In April 2020, the Supreme Court said that oral argument in the ''Mazars'' case and other cases would be heard by telephone.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Supreme Court To Hear Arguments By Telephone, Including On Trump's Financial Records|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/13/833292153/supreme-court-to-hear-arguments-by-telephone-including-on-trumps-financial-recor|last=Totenberg|first=Nina|date=13 April 2020|website=NPR.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Press Releases - April 13, 2020 - Supreme Court of the United States|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/publicinfo/press/pressreleases/pr_04-13-20|last=|first=|date=|website=[[SupremeCourt.gov]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The oral arguments for the consolidated ''Trump v. Mazars'' and ''Trump v. Deutsche Bank AG'', as well as ''Trump v. Vance'', were heard on May 12.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trump v. Mazars USA, LLP|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/trump-v-mazars/|website=SCOTUSblog|language=en|access-date=2020-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The stakes of Trump's tax return case couldn't be higher|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/05/11/opinions/trump-tax-returns-supreme-court-stakes-honig/index.html|last=Honig|first=Elie|date=11 May 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref> In arguing against the need for subpoenas for tax returns, Deputy Solicitor General Jeffrey Wall repeatedly cited that they presented "dangers of harassing and distracting and undermining the President".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lederman |first1=Marty |title=Trump’s DOJ Says the President Would Be “Undermined” if His Tax Records Were Revealed |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/05/trumps-doj-mazars-tax-returns-revealed.html |accessdate=May 16, 2020 |work=[[Slate (website)|Slate]] |date=May 15, 2020}}</ref>
Congressional subpoenas related to this case will expire with the end of the 116th Congress at the end of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/trump-supreme-court-mazars-deutsche-bank-vance-delay.html|title=The Coronavirus May Keep Trump’s Financial Records Under Wraps Forever|last=Stahl|first=Jeremy|date=2020-03-16|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>
