{{short description|Donald Trump's activities as a media personality}} {{Donald Trump series|state=collapsed}}
Before entering politics and ultimately becoming the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|current president]] of the United States, [[Donald Trump]] pursued a career as a [[media personality]]. He [[Bibliography of Donald Trump|released]] several [[Ghostwriting|ghostwritten]] books, most prominently ''[[The Art of the Deal]]'' (1987). Starting in the 1990s, he was a regular guest on the ''[[Howard Stern Show]]'' and other [[talk shows]], promoted the [[professional wrestling]] company [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]], and made several [[cameo appearance|cameo]] [[Donald Trump filmography|film and TV appearances]]. From 2004 to 2015, Trump hosted ''[[The Apprentice (American TV series)|The Apprentice]]'', a [[reality show]] in which contestants competed on [[business]]-related tasks.
== Books ==
{{Main|Bibliography of Donald Trump}}
Trump's first ghostwritten book, ''[[The Art of the Deal]]'' (1987), was on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Seller list]] for 48 weeks. According to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', "The book expanded Trump's renown far beyond New York City, promoting an image of himself as a successful dealmaker and tycoon." [[Tony Schwartz (author)|Tony Schwartz]], who is credited as co-author, later said he did all the writing, backed by [[Howard Kaminsky]], then-head of [[Random House]], the book's publisher.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/07/25/donald-trumps-ghostwriter-tells-all |title=Donald Trump's Ghostwriter Tells All |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Jane |last=Mayer |authorlink=Jane Mayer |date=July 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921030658/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/07/25/donald-trumps-ghostwriter-tells-all |archive-date=September 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two further lesser memoirs were published in 1990 and 1997.
== Professional wrestling ==
Trump has had a sporadic relationship with [[professional wrestling]] promotion [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]] and its owners [[Vince McMahon|Vince]] and [[Linda McMahon]] since the late 1980s; in 1988 and 1989, [[WrestleMania IV]] and [[WrestleMania V|V]], which took place at the [[Boardwalk Hall|Atlantic City Convention Hall]], were billed in storyline as taking place at the nearby [[Trump Plaza Hotel and Casino|Trump Plaza]].<ref name="myth">{{cite news |last=Lelinwalla |first=Mark |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/138117/20160304/donald-trumps-history-wwe.htm |title=Looking Back At Donald Trump's WWE Career |website=Tech Times |date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=July 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707073217/https://www.techtimes.com/articles/138117/20160304/donald-trumps-history-wwe.htm |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=wwebio>{{cite web |url=https://www.wwe.com/superstars/donald-trump |title=Donald Trump bio |website=[[WWE]] |accessdate=March 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312223438/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/donald-trump |archive-date=March 12, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2004, Trump appeared for a live interview at [[WrestleMania XX]], conducted by [[Jesse Ventura]], a former wrestler and former [[Governor of Minnesota]].<ref name="myth"/><ref name="chief_heel">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Chris |last2=Wetherbee |first2=Brandon |url=https://slate.com/culture/2016/12/donald-trump-learned-his-political-moves-from-wwe.html |title=Heel in Chief |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=December 9, 2016 |access-date=March 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044130/https://slate.com/culture/2016/12/donald-trump-learned-his-political-moves-from-wwe.html |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>
In 2007, Trump participated in the "Battle of the Billionaires" storyline [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] against Vince McMahon, this led to Trump headlining [[WrestleMania 23]].<ref name="myth"/><ref name="chief_heel"/> At the event, Trump's representative wrestler, [[Bobby Lashley]], defeated McMahon's representative wrestler, [[Umaga (wrestler)|Umaga]], therefore McMahon was shaved bald by Trump as both men had [[Professional wrestling match types#Luchas de apuestas|wagered their hair on the outcome of the match]]. Guest referee [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] then attacked Trump with the ''Stone Cold Stunner'' wrestling move.<ref name="myth"/> In 2009, Trump participated in a storyline in which he bought WWE's flagship television program ''[[WWE Raw]]'' from Vince McMahon, then re-sold it back shortly after.<ref name="myth"/>
Trump was inducted into the celebrity wing of the [[WWE Hall of Fame (2013)|WWE Hall of Fame in 2013]].<ref name="chief_heel"/> As president, Trump in 2016 appointed Linda McMahon to his Cabinet as [[Administrator of the Small Business Administration]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jacob |last=Pramuk |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/12/07/trump-picks-wrestling-magnate-linda-mcmahon-to-lead-small-business-administration.html |title=Trump picks wrestling magnate Linda McMahon to lead Small Business Administration |work=[[CNBC]] |date=December 7, 2016 |access-date=April 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709114552/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/12/07/trump-picks-wrestling-magnate-linda-mcmahon-to-lead-small-business-administration.html |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>
== ''The Apprentice'' == [[File:Trump and Rodman 2009.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Trump with [[Dennis Rodman]] for ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 8)|Celebrity Apprentice]]'' in 2009]] {{main|The Apprentice (American TV series)}}
In 2003, Trump became the co-producer and host of ''The Apprentice'', a [[reality show]] in which contestants competed for a one-year management job with the Trump Organization, and Trump weeded out applicants with the [[catchphrase]] "You're fired".<ref name="born_7-17-16">{{cite news |last1=Grynbaum |first1=Michael M. |last2=Parker |first2=Ashley |author2link=Ashley Parker |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/business/media/donald-trump-apprentice.html |title=Donald Trump the Political Showman, Born on 'The Apprentice' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 16, 2016 |accessdate=July 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708193849/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/business/media/donald-trump-apprentice.html |archive-date=July 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He later co-hosted ''[[The Celebrity Apprentice]]'', in which celebrities competed to win money for charities.<ref name="born_7-17-16" />
== Acting ==
{{Main|Donald Trump filmography}}
Trump has made [[cameo appearances]] in eight films and television shows<ref name=Atlantic>{{cite news |first=Adrienne |last=LaFrance |title=Three Decades of Donald Trump Film and TV Cameos |date=December 21, 2015 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/three-decades-of-donald-trump-film-and-tv-cameos/421257/ |access-date=April 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193247/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/three-decades-of-donald-trump-film-and-tv-cameos/421257/ |archive-date=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lockett |first=Dee |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/06/donald-trump-was-in-the-little-rascals.html |title=Yes, Donald Trump Did Actually Play a Spoiled Rich Kid's Dad in The Little Rascals |work=Vulture |date=June 21, 2016 |accessdate=July 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714193322/http://www.vulture.com/2016/06/donald-trump-was-in-the-little-rascals.html |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and performed a song as a ''[[Green Acres]]'' character with [[Megan Mullally]] at the [[57th Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shanley |first=Patrick |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/megan-mullally-donald-trump-emmys-stephen-colbert-2016-12 |title=Emmys Flashback: When Trump Sang the 'Green Acres' Theme in Overalls |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 15, 2016 |accessdate=July 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714192950/http://www.businessinsider.com/megan-mullally-donald-trump-emmys-stephen-colbert-2016-12 |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> This is due to his demand that he be allowed to cameo in any movie that features Trump Tower, even just in the skyline. Actor [[Matt Damon]] claims that these scenes are usually cut in [[post-production]]. <ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/09/02/matt-damon-donald-trump-movie-cameos/628123001/</ref>
== Talk shows ==
Starting in the 1990s, Trump was a guest about 24 times on the nationally syndicated ''[[Howard Stern Show]]''.<ref name="Kranish">{{cite book |last1=Kranish |first1=Michael |last2=Fisher |first2=Marc |title=Trump Revealed: The Definitive Biography of the 45th President |date=2017 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=978-1-5011-5652-6 |pages=166 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x2jUDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA166 |language=en}}</ref> He also had his own short-form talk radio program called ''[[Trumped!]]'' (one to two minutes on weekdays) from 2004 to 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.people.com/people/article/0,,632500,00.html |title=The Donald to Get New Wife, Radio Show |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=April 29, 2004 |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |first=Stephen M. |last=Silverman |authorlink=Stephen M. Silverman |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216062730/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,632500,00.html |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><!-- Only sources I find are from 2004 like this: https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040607005748/en/Trumped!-Donald-Trump-Biggest-Launch-Radio-History --><ref>{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Tedeschi |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/06/technology/now-for-sale-online-the-art-of-the-vacation.html |title=Now for Sale Online, the Art of the Vacation |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 6, 2006 |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021190854/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/06/technology/now-for-sale-online-the-art-of-the-vacation.html |archive-date=October 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011, he was given a weekly unpaid guest commentator spot on ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' that continued until he started his presidential candidacy in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Montopoli |first=Brian |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/donald-trump-gets-regular-fox-news-spot/ |title=Donald Trump gets regular Fox News spot |website=[[CBS News]] |date=April 1, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708220815/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/donald-trump-gets-regular-fox-news-spot/ |archive-date=July 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grossman |first1=Matt |last2=Hopkins |first2=David A. |title=How the conservative media is taking over the Republican Party |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/09/09/how-the-conservative-media-is-taking-over-the-republican-party/ |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019164220/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/09/09/how-the-conservative-media-is-taking-over-the-republican-party/ |archive-date=October 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>
